<div1 type="letter">

<pb facs="nei.j4c.62.26" />

<fw type="curatorial">26</fw>

<opener>
<dateline>
5835 Vine Street
Lincoln, Nebraska 68505
April 23, 1971
</dateline>

<address>
<addrLine>Mr. Fred Lee</addrLine>
<addrLine>Kansas City, Missouri</addrLine>
</address>

<salute>Dear Fred:</salute>
</opener>
<p>Many hearty thanks for your glowing telegram of April 21. I prize it greatly and it will go among the other beautiful expressions of regard that I have received for the anniversary of my laureateship. I wish you could have been present for this. It was the most remarkable affair of the sort I had ever seen with all of the city and state officials present. I enclose a program which will give you some idea of what happened but there was a "go" in the whole affair that I cannot describe. It needed to be experienced.</p>

<p>And then &#8212; that lordly capitol building.</p>

<p>I expect to be seeing you one of these times although I don't know when. I will be at Park College on the 12th of May. I have been going pretty hard and am tired but there is plenty of compensation, and I am grateful.</p>
<closer>
<salute>With the old affection, your friend</salute>

<signed>John G. Neihardt</signed>
</closer>
</div1>
